      Citi Revlon
   =20
 =20

In 2016, Revlon Inc. borrowed money from some banks and hedge funds. Citigr=
oup Inc. was the administrative agent on the loan, in charge of doing stuff=
 like forwarding payments from Revlon to the lenders. Revlon ran into some =
financial trouble and set out to modify its debt in an aggressive=C2=A0way =
that disadvantaged some of the lenders on that term loan. This made those l=
enders mad, and they geared up to sue Revlon. Just as they were about to su=
e, in August 2020, Citi=C2=A0accidentally paid off the whole loan =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0$900 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0with its own money. We talked about this =
in detail   last year, and it still makes me laugh and cringe.=C2=A0Citi wa=
s helping Revlon with the loan modification, and its loan-modification=C2=
=A0software had an unbelievably janky user interface, and a Citi back-offic=
e person pressed the wrong button and paid off the whole loan. Oops.
The next day Citi realized what it had done and emailed the lenders to be l=
ike =E2=80=9Csorry that money wasn=E2=80=99t meant for you, please send it =
back.=E2=80=9D This is a thing that happens! In high finance, sometimes sop=
histicated counterparties send each other mistaken transfers, and then they=
 email and say =E2=80=9Csorry about that, wrong number,=E2=80=9D and then t=
he counterparties send it back. These people deal with each other repeatedl=
y, and you can=E2=80=99t just=C2=A0keep=C2=A0money that a=C2=A0bank sends y=
ou by accident, both as a legal matter and as a norm of politeness. But in =
this particular case the=C2=A0lenders really wanted the money (because Revl=
on was in distress, the loan was worth a fraction of its face value, and ge=
tting paid off early at par was good) and were already pretty mad at Citi (=
because it was helping Revlon do the aggressive modification that disadvant=
aged them), so lenders who held about $500 million of the loan didn=E2=80=
=99t send the money back to Citi and said =E2=80=9Csee you in court.=E2=80=
=9D
They did, of course, and last February they   won a pretty shocking victory=
 in federal court in New York. The judge found that under the New York rule=
 of =E2=80=9Cdischarge for value=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes called t=
he =E2=80=9CBanque Worms=E2=80=9D doctrine, after the pleasingly named lead=
ing case =E2=80=94=C2=A0the hedge funds were entitled to keep the money bec=
ause=C2=A0they really did have a loan out to Revlon, and they didn=E2=80=99=
t immediately know that this repayment was wrong (not until Citi emailed th=
em the next day), so, sure, they could keep it. Citi appealed this ruling.
Meanwhile, it was a mess.=C2=A0Revlon really was in financial distress; ult=
imately it filed for bankruptcy this June. As Revlon was trying to renegoti=
ate its debts with its lenders, it faced a strange problem, which is that  =
 it didn=E2=80=99t know who its lenders were. What happened to that $500 mi=
llion debt? Perhaps=C2=A0Citi would win on appeal, and the original lenders=
 (hedge funds, etc.) would return the money; then they would still be Revlo=
n=E2=80=99s creditors. Or perhaps=C2=A0Citi would lose on appeal, and it wo=
uld have effectively bought the loan from those hedge funds, making Citi Re=
vlon=E2=80=99s creditor. Or Citi would lose on appeal, and it=C2=A0hadn=E2=
=80=99t=C2=A0bought the loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps it had just paid it off=
 out of the goodness of its heart, and Revlon didn=E2=80=99t owe anyone tha=
t $500 million. (A weird, but not completely indefensible, reading of the s=
ituation.)=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s tough to negotiate a debt restructuring or a b=
ankruptcy plan when you aren=E2=80=99t sure if you have a $500 million debt=
 or not, and if you do you don=E2=80=99t know who you owe it to.
Last Thursday, Citi won its appeal. You can read  the opinions=C2=A0here; t=
hey come to 131 pages, but the gist=C2=A0is pretty simple. Here=E2=80=99s h=
ow the Banque Worms case explains=C2=A0the discharge-for-value doctrine:
When a beneficiary receives money to which it is entitled and has no knowle=
dge that the money was erroneously wired, the beneficiary should not have t=
o wonder whether it may retain the funds; rather, such a beneficiary should=
 be able to consider the transfer of funds as a final and complete transact=
ion, not subject to revocation.
So if you want to keep money sent to you in error under Banque Worms,=C2=A0=
there are two requirements: You have to be entitled to the money, and you h=
ave to have no knowledge that it was sent in error. The appeals court found=
 that neither requirement=C2=A0was true here. The Revlon creditors were=C2=
=A0not=C2=A0entitled to the money: They had a loan out to Revlon, sure,=C2=
=A0but it was not due until 2023, so they weren=E2=80=99t entitled to get p=
aid when Citi wired them the money in 2020. And they surely had some indica=
tion that it was sent in error =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was paid early, out of the=
 blue, with no notice =E2=80=94=C2=A0so they should have at least checked w=
ith Citi before running out to spend the money. So, no discharge-for-value,=
 no Banque Worms, they have to return the money.
One judge on the panel, Michael Park, wrote a separate concurrence saying t=
hat this was all pretty obvious and the court shouldn=E2=80=99t have taken =
so long:

In my view, this is a straightforward case that many smart people have gros=
sly overcomplicated and that we should have decided many months ago. ...=C2=
=A0A recipient of mistakenly transferred funds cannot invoke the discharge-=
for-value defense =E2=80=A6 unless and until it has a present entitlement a=
gainst the debtor. Put simply, you don=E2=80=99t get to keep money sent to =
you by mistake unless you=E2=80=99re entitled to it anyway. =E2=80=A6
This delay has had dire repercussions for Revlon, the company at the center=
 of this case. Both sides contend that through subrogation, the district co=
urt=E2=80=99s judgment has put Citibank in the shoes of the Creditors, obli=
ging Revlon to pay Citibank instead and transferring to Citibank the credit=
 risk of Revlon=E2=80=99s distressed debt. A company like Revlon=E2=80=94no=
 stranger to restructuring its debts=E2=80=94would normally try to negotiat=
e with its creditors when struggling to meet its obligations. But Revlon ne=
ver recognized Citibank=E2=80=99s subrogation claim, and even if it had, Ci=
tibank would have been at best a substitute creditor, whose claim (if any) =
would revert to Defendants once Citibank finally reclaimed its funds. Revlo=
n cannot secure additional senior financing without the consent of a majori=
ty of the 2016 Term Creditors, but for the past two years, no one has been =
able to agree on who would constitute such a majority. So Revlon =E2=80=9Ce=
ffectively has had, since August 11, 2020, no 2016 Term Loan[] counterparty=
 with which it can negotiate,=E2=80=9D and on June 15, 2022, Revlon filed f=
or Chapter 11 bankruptcy.

Is Revlon bankrupt because the appeals court took more than a year to write=
 this opinion? Eh, I don=E2=80=99t know, probably not, but it didn=E2=80=99=
t help.
One way that you know the appeals court is right and the district court was=
 wrong is that the loan market very quickly reacted to the decision last ye=
ar. No other bank wanted to find itself in this situation due to a fat fing=
er, so =E2=80=9CRevlon blockers=E2=80=9D were added to new loan documents, =
explicitly saying that if the administrative agent=C2=A0sends money in erro=
r then the lenders have to send it back.=C2=A0I   wrote last year:

Look: Obviously! There is no earthly reason that those funds should be able=
 to keep the money, except that there happens to be a weird doctrine of New=
 York law that lets them keep it.
  [1]
 As a former lawyer I am tempted to say, sure, fine, whatever,=C2=A0counter=
intuitive old doctrines are what make law school fun and keep lawyers emplo=
yed. =E2=80=9CCiti just sent us money by mistake, do we have to give it bac=
k,=E2=80=9D the hedge fund analyst asks, and instead of saying =E2=80=9Cof =
course duh we live in society,=E2=80=9D the portfolio manager replies =E2=
=80=9Chang on, let me consult with a lawyer,=E2=80=9D and the lawyer says =
=E2=80=9Chang on, let me consult with my firm=E2=80=99s specialist in Finde=
rs Keepers Law,=E2=80=9D and the Finders Keepers specialist consults some d=
usty old tomes of arcane lore and says =E2=80=9Clemme tell you about the do=
ctrine of discharge for value.=E2=80=9D And she bills the hedge fund $2,000=
 an hour and is=C2=A0absolutely worth it.=C2=A0We live in a particular kind=
 of society.
But this doctrine is dumb and no one in the world of syndicated lending act=
ually meant to sign up for it; =E2=80=9Cif you send us the wrong money we w=
ill keep it=E2=80=9D is not a rule that anyone wanted built into their loan=
 documents. It did not occur to anyone to opt out of it=E2=80=94it did not =
occur to anyone, outside of the small fellowship of Finders Keepers lawyers=
, that this rule even existed=E2=80=94until it cost Citi $500 million.=C2=
=A0But now everyone is extremely aware of it, the big banks want to opt out=
, they have consulted with their own Finders Keepers lawyers, they have put=
 the opt-out language into the contracts, and the other lenders don=E2=80=
=99t really have a choice. What are they going to do, object? =E2=80=9CNo, =
if you send us money by accident, we=E2=80=99d prefer to keep it=E2=80=9D? =
It=E2=80=99s just not a reasonable ask. It=E2=80=99s the=C2=A0law, sure=E2=
=80=94at least by default=E2=80=94but it=E2=80=99s not reasonable.

And this =E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9CRevlon blocker=E2=80=9D saying that yo=
u have to give back the money =E2=80=94 has become an almost universal rule=
. Law professor  Eric Talley found that there are about =E2=80=9Cbetween 15=
0 and 200 Revlon blockers disclosed per month among publicly listed compani=
es,=E2=80=9D versus just one=C2=A0loan agreement that explicitly adopted th=
e discharge-for-value rule. Nobody in the loan market=C2=A0really=C2=A0thou=
ght that Revlon=E2=80=99s lenders should get to keep this money, and now th=
ey don=E2=80=99t.

