   =20
      Twitter v. Musk
   =20
 =20

The state of play is:
=09Elon Musk =09=09wants to get out of his deal to buy Twitter Inc. for $44=
 billion for reasons of his own. The market crashed since he signed the dea=
l, making him less rich and Twitter less valuable, so he doesn=E2=80=99t wa=
nt to pay the $44 billion. Or he has realized that owning Twitter would be =
a headache and not that fun. Or he=E2=80=99s gotten bored, or he just think=
s it=E2=80=99s funnier to get out of the deal. I don=E2=80=99t know.=09The =
definitive merger agreement that Musk signed does not allow Musk to get out=
 of the deal because he changed his mind.=09So he has spent the last few mo=
nths looking for excuses that=C2=A0do=C2=A0let him out of the deal. If Twit=
ter committed fraud to trick him into signing the merger agreement, or if i=
t has suffered certain kinds of =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D o=
n its business, or if it made misrepresentations in the merger agreement th=
at would likely lead to a material adverse effect, or if it has violated it=
s covenants under the merger agreement, then Musk can walk away from the de=
al.=09Musk found some excuses and  sent Twitter a letter terminating the me=
rger agreement, and Twitter=C2=A0wrote back to say =E2=80=9Cno these excuse=
s are no good, you still have to close, see you in court,=E2=80=9D and ther=
e=E2=80=99s a trial scheduled to start Oct. 17.=09The first set of excuses =
that Musk came up with =E2=80=94=C2=A0claims that Twitter is lying about ho=
w many spam bot accounts it has, claims that Twitter has   violated its cov=
enant to give Musk information that he asks for (by not giving him enough s=
pam bot information), claims that Twitter has violated its covenant to oper=
ate in the =E2=80=9Cordinary course of business=E2=80=9D (by firing a few p=
eople) =E2=80=94=C2=A0were not very good.=09But he kind of gets unlimited c=
hances, and he keeps looking around for new excuses. And he=E2=80=99s the r=
ichest person in the world, so if you find an excuse for him, that seems ca=
reer-enhancing.=09Last month, Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatko, Twitter=
=E2=80=99s former head of security,   publicized a whistle-blower complaint=
 that seemed weirdly written for Musk. (It has a section titled =E2=80=9CLy=
ing about Bots to Elon Musk,=E2=80=9D even though Zatko seems to agree with=
 Twitter that its actual disclosures about bots are accurate.)=C2=A0Zatko m=
ade a bunch of claims about Twitter violating legal settlements, having bad=
 information-security practices and hiding them from the board and sharehol=
ders, misusing intellectual property, all sorts of miscellaneous stuff. Cou=
ld any of those things   amount to fraud, or a material adverse effect? May=
be?=09So Musk  sent Twitter another termination letter, saying, in effect, =
I know I=E2=80=99ve already terminated this merger agreement for the bot st=
uff, but just in case I am terminating it again for the Mudge stuff. And Tw=
itter sent back  a letter saying =E2=80=9Cno,=E2=80=9D and this stuff   got=
 added to the list of issues in the trial, which is still scheduled to star=
t Oct. 17.

That=E2=80=99s the state of play as of when we last discussed this, way bac=
k   last Wednesday. Here is the update from Friday:
=09It turns out that on June 28, Twitter signed a severance agreement with =
Zatko and paid him $7.75 million.=09The merger agreement (section 6.1(e)) s=
ays that Twitter can=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cgrant or provide any severance or t=
ermination payments or benefits to any [employee]=C2=A0other than the payme=
nt of severance amounts or benefits in the ordinary course of business cons=
istent with past practice=E2=80=9D without Musk=E2=80=99s permission.
=09Twitter didn=E2=80=99t ask Musk for permission.=09Another covenant breac=
h!=C2=A0=09Musk duly  sent Twitter another letter terminating the merger ag=
reement for the third time.=09Twitter sent Musk  another letter back saying=
 =E2=80=9Cno.=E2=80=9D

I have to say that, of Musk=E2=80=99s excuses so far, this is probably my f=
avorite.=C2=A0The bot ones are   really bad, man. Zatko=E2=80=99s substanti=
ve claims seem like run-of-the-mill=C2=A0security grousing, not enough to c=
onstitute fraud or a material adverse effect. Musk=E2=80=99s previous claim=
s about covenant violations seem like silly nitpicks. But this one has a ce=
rtain intuitive appeal. This is: =E2=80=9CYour head of security came to you=
 with damning revelations and to keep him quiet you paid him $7.75 million.=
 That is certainly not an ordinary-course payment, and you were obligated, =
under the terms of the contract, to get my approval for non-ordinary-course=
 severance payments. But you didn=E2=80=99t because you knew these damning =
revelations were damning, and you didn=E2=80=99t want me to see them and wa=
lk away.=E2=80=9D That=C2=A0does=C2=A0sound like a bad covenant breach!
We have not seen Twitter=E2=80=99s defense yet, and it=E2=80=99s not even c=
lear that this will be added to the pile of things to be disputed at trial.=
=C2=A0I assume that the defense is that this $7.75 million payment is in fa=
ct =E2=80=9Cin the ordinary course of business consistent with past practic=
e=E2=80=9D; in particular, to the extent that the $7.75 million is mostly  =
deferred=C2=A0compensation that he was entitled to anyway=C2=A0then it coul=
d in fact be pretty ordinary-course. (That  seems to be the case: =E2=80=9C=
The settlement came after monthslong mediation over tens of millions of dol=
lars in potential pay.=E2=80=9D)
Still if I were a company in a merger agreement and I was about to sign a $=
7.75 million severance agreement with my aggrieved former head of informati=
on security I would definitely want to run it by the buyer first. That is j=
ust a bad surprise; you don=E2=80=99t want to look like you=E2=80=99re hidi=
ng the ball. In fairness to Twitter, by this point things were already bad:=
   Musk tweeted that the deal was =E2=80=9Ctemporarily on hold=E2=80=9D bac=
k in May, and by June 28=C2=A0Musk and Twitter were exchanging  increasingl=
y snippy letters that were inevitably going to end with Musk terminating th=
e deal. If Twitter=C2=A0had=C2=A0run the severance agreement by him, he wou=
ld have said no, and he would have used it as another excuse to terminate. =
And now he=E2=80=99s doing that anyway.
Still if none of the other stuff had happened =E2=80=94=C2=A0if Musk was wo=
rking diligently to close the deal and then a whistle-blower showed up sayi=
ng =E2=80=9CI have lots of evidence that Twitter is doing fraud, and they p=
aid me $7.75 million to go away and kept it secret from you=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0then you would think, =E2=80=9Chuh, yes, that seems bad, and if Mu=
sk wanted to get out of the deal now I wouldn=E2=80=99t blame him.=E2=80=9D=
 That=E2=80=99s not the situation we=E2=80=99re in, but you can see why Mus=
k would add this to the pile.
The main point I want to make here is that this is very generalizable. If y=
ou know something bad about Twitter, or if you have been reading  the merge=
r agreement online and think there=E2=80=99s a clause of the agreement that=
 Musk can use to get out of it, shoot him a tweet. If you=E2=80=99re right,=
 or frankly if you=E2=80=99re wrong, his lawyers can put your claims into a=
 letter and send it to Twitter saying =E2=80=9CI know we=E2=80=99ve already=
 terminated this agreement three times, but we=E2=80=99re doing=C2=A0one mo=
re.=E2=80=9D Musk can terminate as often as he likes
  [2]
; if he terminates the agreement 100 times with 100 excuses and 99 of them =
are laughed out of court, but the 100th works, then that=E2=80=99s good eno=
ugh for him.

