  [1] There isn=E2=80=99t. When I wrote this, the district court had said t=
hat there was, but the appeals court sensibly found that that=E2=80=99s not=
 really what New York law says.


  [2] There is an important caveat to this that I am going to put here beca=
use it is technical. Musk actually is *not* allowed to terminate the agreem=
ent if *he* is =E2=80=9Cin material breach of any of [his] representations,=
 warranties, covenants or agreements=E2=80=9D under the agreement (Section =
8.1(d)). And each time Twitter replies to his termination letters, they mak=
e sure to emphasize that he is in breach of his obligations, in particular =
his obligations to use his reasonable best efforts to close the deal. I thi=
nk that this is undoubtedly true, and that Twitter is right that he is tech=
nically not allowed to terminate =E2=80=94 *especially* if his *first* set =
of excuses (bots, etc.) are bad. (If he terminated wrongfully and stopped t=
rying to close the deal, then he=E2=80=99s in breach; if he terminated righ=
tfully then maybe he isn=E2=80=99t.) So I agree with Twitter that Musk can=
=E2=80=99t technically terminate the deal for his third set of excuses. But=
 I don=E2=80=99t think this matters that much, because Musk=E2=80=99s argum=
ents for termination are also arguments about the conditions to closing not=
 being satisfied. So as a technical matter if he is right about, say, the s=
everance payment, then I think what that means is (1) he doesn=E2=80=99t ha=
ve to close the deal but (2) he can=E2=80=99t terminate it. That leaves it =
in limbo, and presumably if that were true =E2=80=94 like if a court defini=
tively found that Musk is in breach and can=E2=80=99t terminate, but also t=
hat he=E2=80=99s right that he doesn=E2=80=99t have to close =E2=80=94 then=
 Twitter and Musk would just agree to terminate rather than sitting in limb=
o forever. I think people sometimes read the you-can=E2=80=99t-terminate-if=
-you=E2=80=99re-breaching language to mean that Musk would have to buy Twit=
ter even if he could definitively prove that it=E2=80=99s a massive fraud, =
because his own breaches make all of his arguments invalid, and I think tha=
t=E2=80=99s probably wrong.


  [3] One salient objection to the model is: Well, *Theranos* never went pu=
blic, and Elizabeth Holmes was nonetheless charged and   convicted for doin=
g fraud. I do think that is an unusual outcome. I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=
=80=99s really the law that you can do whatever wild fraud you want in a VC=
-backed startup, but is there a sense in which it is socially acceptable?  =
Maybe, a little?


