10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Citi Revlon</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2016, Revlon Inc. borrowed money from some =
banks and hedge funds. Citigroup Inc. was the administrative agent on the l=
oan, in charge of doing stuff like forwarding payments from Revlon to the l=
enders. Revlon ran into some financial trouble and set out to modify its de=
bt in an aggressive=C2=A0way that disadvantaged some of the lenders on that=
 term loan. This made those lenders mad, and they geared up to sue Revlon. =
Just as they were about to sue, in August 2020, Citi=C2=A0accidentally paid=
 off the whole loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0$900 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0with its own=
 money. We talked about this in detail <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/29026572.268542/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMTcvY2l0aS1jYW4tdC1oYXZlLWl0cy05MDAtbWlsbGlvb=
i1iYWNrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MTIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nv=
dXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDkxMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd65f07cb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  last year</a>, and it still ma=
kes me laugh and cringe.=C2=A0Citi was helping Revlon with the loan modific=
ation, and its loan-modification=C2=A0software had an unbelievably janky us=
er interface, and a Citi back-office person pressed the wrong button and pa=
id off the whole loan. Oops.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The next day Citi realized what it had done an=
d emailed the lenders to be like =E2=80=9Csorry that money wasn=E2=80=99t m=
eant for you, please send it back.=E2=80=9D This is a thing that happens! I=
n high finance, sometimes sophisticated counterparties send each other mist=
aken transfers, and then they email and say =E2=80=9Csorry about that, wron=
g number,=E2=80=9D and then the counterparties send it back. These people d=
eal with each other repeatedly, and you can=E2=80=99t just=C2=A0<em>keep=C2=
=A0</em>money that a=C2=A0bank sends you by accident, both as a legal matte=
r and as a norm of politeness. But in this particular case the=C2=A0lenders=
 really wanted the money (because Revlon was in distress, the loan was wort=
h a fraction of its face value, and getting paid off early at par was good)=
 and were already pretty mad at Citi (because it was helping Revlon do the =
aggressive modification that disadvantaged them), so lenders who held about=
 $500 million of the loan didn=E2=80=99t send the money back to Citi and sa=
id =E2=80=9Csee you in court.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They did, of course, and last February they <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29026572.268542/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMTcvY2l0aS1=
jYW4tdC1oYXZlLWl0cy05MDAtbWlsbGlvbi1iYWNrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MTIyMl9NT05FWVNUVU=
ZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDkxM=
iZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCd65f07cb" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">  won a pretty shocking victory</a> in federal court in New York. The jud=
ge found that under the New York rule of =E2=80=9Cdischarge for value=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes called the =E2=80=9CBanque Worms=E2=80=9D doct=
rine, after the pleasingly named leading case =E2=80=94=C2=A0the hedge fund=
s were entitled to keep the money because=C2=A0they really did have a loan =
out to Revlon, and they didn=E2=80=99t immediately know that this repayment=
 was wrong (not until Citi emailed them the next day), so, sure, they could=
 keep it. Citi appealed this ruling.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, it was a mess.=C2=A0Revlon really w=
as in financial distress; ultimately it filed for bankruptcy this June. As =
Revlon was trying to renegotiate its debts with its lenders, it faced a str=
ange problem, which is that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/29026572.268542/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fyd=
GljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMjEvY2l0aS1hbmQtcmV2bG9uLWFyZS1pbi1tdXJreS13YXRlcnM_Y21w=
aWQ9QkJEMDkxMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3N=
sZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTEyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB41760e77" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  it didn=E2=80=99t know who its lenders were=
</a>. What happened to that $500 million debt? Perhaps=C2=A0Citi would win =
on appeal, and the original lenders (hedge funds, etc.) would return the mo=
ney; then they would still be Revlon=E2=80=99s creditors. Or perhaps=C2=A0C=
iti would lose on appeal, and it would have effectively bought the loan fro=
m those hedge funds, making Citi Revlon=E2=80=99s creditor. Or Citi would l=
ose on appeal, and it=C2=A0<em>hadn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>bought the loan =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0perhaps it had just paid it off out of the goodness of its hear=
t, and Revlon didn=E2=80=99t owe anyone that $500 million. (A weird, but no=
t completely indefensible, reading of the situation.)=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s tou=
gh to negotiate a debt restructuring or a bankruptcy plan when you aren=E2=
=80=99t sure if you have a $500 million debt or not, and if you do you don=
=E2=80=99t know who you owe it to.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last Thursday, Citi won its appeal. You can re=
ad <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29026572.268542=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2EyLnVzY291cnRzLmdvdi9kZWNpc2lvbnMvaXN5c3F1ZXJ5L2M5ZGZmNm=
IyLThkYjgtNDQ4NS05YmFiLTAwZWU1NmFlYzRhNC8xL2RvYy8yMS00ODdfY29tcGxldGVfb3BuL=
nBkZiN4bWw9aHR0cDovL3d3dy5jYTIudXNjb3VydHMuZ292OjQ0My9pc3lzcXVlcnkvYzlkZmY2=
YjItOGRiOC00NDg1LTliYWItMDBlZTU2YWVjNGE0LzE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf6aa8e=
c9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> the opinions</a>=C2=A0here; they come to 131 pages, but the g=
ist=C2=A0is pretty simple. Here=E2=80=99s how the Banque Worms case explain=
s=C2=A0the discharge-for-value doctrine:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When a beneficiary receives money =
to which it is entitled and has no knowledge that the money was erroneously=
 wired, the beneficiary should not have to wonder whether it may retain the=
 funds; rather, such a beneficiary should be able to consider the transfer =
of funds as a final and complete transaction, not subject to revocation.</p=
></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if you want to keep money sent to you in er=
ror under Banque Worms,=C2=A0there are two requirements: You have to be ent=
itled to the money, and you have to have no knowledge that it was sent in e=
rror. The appeals court found that neither requirement=C2=A0was true here. =
The Revlon creditors were=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>entitled to the money: The=
y had a loan out to Revlon, sure,=C2=A0but it was not due until 2023, so th=
ey weren=E2=80=99t entitled to get paid when Citi wired them the money in 2=
020. And they surely had some indication that it was sent in error =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0it was paid early, out of the blue, with no notice =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
so they should have at least checked with Citi before running out to spend =
the money. So, no discharge-for-value, no Banque Worms, they have to return=
 the money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One judge on the panel, Michael Park, wrote a =
separate concurrence saying that this was all pretty obvious and the court =
shouldn=E2=80=99t have taken so long:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In my view, this is a straightforward case tha=
t many smart people have grossly overcomplicated and that we should have de=
cided many months ago. ...=C2=A0A recipient of mistakenly transferred funds=
 cannot invoke the discharge-for-value defense =E2=80=A6 unless and until i=
t has a present entitlement against the debtor. Put simply, you don=E2=80=
=99t get to keep money sent to you by mistake unless you=E2=80=99re entitle=
d to it anyway. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This delay has had dire repercussions for Revl=
on, the company at the center of this case. Both sides contend that through=
 subrogation, the district court=E2=80=99s judgment has put Citibank in the=
 shoes of the Creditors, obliging Revlon to pay Citibank instead and transf=
erring to Citibank the credit risk of Revlon=E2=80=99s distressed debt. A c=
ompany like Revlon=E2=80=94no stranger to restructuring its debts=E2=80=94w=
ould normally try to negotiate with its creditors when struggling to meet i=
ts obligations. But Revlon never recognized Citibank=E2=80=99s subrogation =
claim, and even if it had, Citibank would have been at best a substitute cr=
editor, whose claim (if any) would revert to Defendants once Citibank final=
ly reclaimed its funds. Revlon cannot secure additional senior financing wi=
thout the consent of a majority of the 2016 Term Creditors, but for the pas=
t two years, no one has been able to agree on who would constitute such a m=
ajority. So Revlon =E2=80=9Ceffectively has had, since August 11, 2020, no =
2016 Term Loan[] counterparty with which it can negotiate,=E2=80=9D and on =
June 15, 2022, Revlon filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is Revlon bankrupt because the appeals court t=
ook more than a year to write this opinion? Eh, I don=E2=80=99t know, proba=
bly not, but it didn=E2=80=99t help.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way that you know the appeals court is rig=
ht and the district court was wrong is that the loan market very quickly re=
acted to the decision last year. No other bank wanted to find itself in thi=
s situation due to a fat finger, so =E2=80=9CRevlon blockers=E2=80=9D were =
added to new loan documents, explicitly saying that if the administrative a=
gent=C2=A0sends money in error then the lenders have to send it back.=C2=A0=
I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29026572.268542/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMDMvY2l=
0aS13b24tdC1taXNwbGFjZS01MDAtbWlsbGlvbi1hZ2Fpbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTEyMjJfTU9ORV=
lTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yM=
jA5MTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3c82ce27" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">  wrote last year</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look: Obviously! There is no earthly reason th=
at those funds should be able to keep the money, except that there happens =
to be a weird doctrine of New York law that lets them keep it.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> As a former lawyer I am tempted to say, sure, fine, whatever,=C2=A0cou=
nterintuitive old doctrines are what make law school fun and keep lawyers e=
mployed. =E2=80=9CCiti just sent us money by mistake, do we have to give it=
 back,=E2=80=9D the hedge fund analyst asks, and instead of saying =E2=80=
=9Cof course duh we live in society,=E2=80=9D the portfolio manager replies=
 =E2=80=9Chang on, let me consult with a lawyer,=E2=80=9D and the lawyer sa=
ys =E2=80=9Chang on, let me consult with my firm=E2=80=99s specialist in Fi=
nders Keepers Law,=E2=80=9D and the Finders Keepers specialist consults som=
e dusty old tomes of arcane lore and says =E2=80=9Clemme tell you about the=
 doctrine of discharge for value.=E2=80=9D And she bills the hedge fund $2,=
000 an hour and is=C2=A0<em>absolutely worth it</em>.=C2=A0We live in a par=
ticular kind of society.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this doctrine is dumb and no one in the wo=
rld of syndicated lending actually meant to sign up for it; =E2=80=9Cif you=
 send us the wrong money we will keep it=E2=80=9D is not a rule that anyone=
 wanted built into their loan documents. It did not occur to anyone to opt =
out of it=E2=80=94it did not occur to anyone, outside of the small fellowsh=
ip of Finders Keepers lawyers, that this rule even existed=E2=80=94until it=
 cost Citi $500 million.=C2=A0But now everyone is extremely aware of it, th=
e big banks want to opt out, they have consulted with their own Finders Kee=
pers lawyers, they have put the opt-out language into the contracts, and th=
e other lenders don=E2=80=99t really have a choice. What are they going to =
do, object? =E2=80=9CNo, if you send us money by accident, we=E2=80=99d pre=
fer to keep it=E2=80=9D? It=E2=80=99s just not a reasonable ask. It=E2=80=
=99s the=C2=A0<em>law</em>, sure=E2=80=94at least by default=E2=80=94but it=
=E2=80=99s not reasonable.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And this =E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9CRevlon bl=
ocker=E2=80=9D saying that you have to give back the money =E2=80=94 has be=
come an almost universal rule. Law professor <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29026572.268542/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20v=
c29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTM5MDYyMDE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBef=
8697f1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> Eric Talley found</a> that there are about =E2=80=9Cbetwee=
n 150 and 200 Revlon blockers disclosed per month among publicly listed com=
