<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could have a model of the startup life cyc=
le=C2=A0that goes like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some young visionary weirdo has a dre=
am. She tells this dream to venture capitalists, who decide whether or not =
to give her money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Venture capital=
ists=C2=A0reward, mainly, audacity. The more outrageous her dream is, the m=
ore outrageous=C2=A0<em>she=C2=A0</em>is, the more likely they are to give =
her money. Venture capitalists are=C2=A0philosophically in the business of =
investing in 100 companies and hoping that three of them have 100x returns.=
 Conservative steady earners are not what they want. They want huge world-c=
hanging ideas that will probably fail, but if they succeed will be the next=
 Facebook. Outrageous ambition, unhindered by the boring constraints of the=
 real world, is what they want. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/29026572.268542/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTAtMjMvaG93LWRvLXlvdS1saWtlLXdlLW5vdz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTEy=
MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1=
fdGVybT0yMjA5MTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
0f19cd5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">  Masayoshi Son told Adam Neumann</a> that he =E2=80=9Capp=
reciated how he was crazy,=C2=A0but thought that he needed to be crazier.=
=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the founder is weird =
and visionary enough, she gets money from VCs, and then tries to build her =
dream at a startup.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Most of these =
startups fail, because their dreams are in fact impossible. They close up a=
nd return $0 to their VC investors, who are fine with that. Most startups a=
re=C2=A0<em>supposed=C2=A0</em>to fail. If you don=E2=80=99t have some fail=
ures, you=E2=80=99re not dreaming big enough.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">Some succeed, build a functioning product, find product-market =
fit and get on the road to profitability.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Then they go public, perhaps to raise more money, or perhaps =
just to cash out their founders and VCs.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">The public markets reward, mainly, steadiness and transparency. The =
more outrageous the founder=E2=80=99s ideas, the more nervous they will mak=
e the bankers and lawyers hired to take the company public.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some founders will mature along with their compan=
ies, become more realistic after years in the trenches building products, a=
nd grow into being plausible public-company chief executive officers. Other=
 founders will get kicked out just before the initial public offering; the =
companies will replace them with steady professional CEOs more suited to ru=
n public companies. Others will continue to be excitable weirdos but their =
lawyers will try to rein them in as much as possible.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">It helps that the only companies going public are=C2=A0=
<em>the ones who succeeded:=C2=A0</em>They may not be profitable yet, but t=
hey have a real product, real revenue, demonstrated product-market fit, a g=
ood business plan, etc. So when their excitable weirdo CEOs make outrageous=
 promises, they might actually come true.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t want to say that this model is=
 empirically true in every respect, but I think it has a rough wisdom and i=
s how a lot of people think about startups and venture capital.<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On this model, the very worst thing that could=
 happen to a startup founder might be skipping too quickly from Step 2 to S=
tep 7. You=E2=80=99re a wild-eyed visionary, you wander around telling vent=
ure capitalists outrageous things, they are like =E2=80=9Cyou are so crazy,=
 I love it, be crazier,=E2=80=9D you write down =E2=80=9CBE CRAZIER=E2=80=
=9D on your to-do list, you go home, you go to bed, the next day you wake u=
p and do an IPO: You will be too crazy for the IPO! You need to have a few =
years to mellow and mature between the VCs telling you to be crazy and the =
IPO lawyers telling you to stick to verifiable facts. Adam Neumann never go=
t to take WeWork public; he tried, but there was too much craziness in the =
Neumann-led WeWork for the IPO to work.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And on this model, the SPAC boom =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the rise of special purpose acquisition companies that tend to take unpr=
ofitable startups public=C2=A0<em>early</em>, before they even have a produ=
ct, on the strength of projections about future profits =E2=80=94=C2=A0seem=
s pretty dangerous.</p>
