m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">Section 8.1(d)</a>). And each time Twitter replies to=
 his termination letters, they make sure to emphasize that he is in breach =
of his obligations, in particular his obligations to use his reasonable bes=
t efforts to close the deal. I think that this is undoubtedly true, and tha=
t Twitter is right that he is technically not allowed to terminate =E2=80=
=94 *especially* if his *first* set of excuses (bots, etc.) are bad. (If he=
 terminated wrongfully and stopped trying to close the deal, then he=E2=80=
=99s in breach; if he terminated rightfully then maybe he isn=E2=80=99t.) S=
o I agree with Twitter that Musk can=E2=80=99t technically terminate the de=
al for his third set of excuses. But I don=E2=80=99t think this matters tha=
t much, because Musk=E2=80=99s arguments for termination are also arguments=
 about the conditions to closing not being satisfied. So as a technical mat=
ter if he is right about, say, the severance payment, then I think what tha=
t means is (1) he doesn=E2=80=99t have to close the deal but (2) he can=E2=
=80=99t terminate it. That leaves it in limbo, and presumably if that were =
true =E2=80=94 like if a court definitively found that Musk is in breach an=
d can=E2=80=99t terminate, but also that he=E2=80=99s right that he doesn=
=E2=80=99t have to close =E2=80=94 then Twitter and Musk would just agree t=
o terminate rather than sitting in limbo forever. I think people sometimes =
read the you-can=E2=80=99t-terminate-if-you=E2=80=99re-breaching language t=
o mean that Musk would have to buy Twitter even if he could definitively pr=
ove that it=E2=80=99s a massive fraud, because his own breaches make all of=
 his arguments invalid, and I think that=E2=80=99s probably wrong.</p>
</div>
